It's been a while. This time I'm continuing the "computers that I never had" series to talk about a project that has been sitting on my bench for literally months waiting less busier times to complete: the Philips Telematico NMS3000.

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/telematico.jpg" text="The Philips Telematico NMS3000" >}}

The are a couple of reasons why I bought this relic to work on it: it takes me back to the pre-Internet days of modems, X.25 and Videotex, it's simple enough that I think I can fully understand how it works and make it work, it has near zero information about it on the Internet which will force me to discover things on my own, which I love.

## What is Videotex

[Videotex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Videotex) was an early pre-Internet two-way electronic communication system that allowed users to access information services via the telephone line and a modem and display text and rudimentary graphics on the screen.

A lot of European countries had Videotex services, France had the famous [Minitel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minitel), and in Portugal one was provided by [Telepac](https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Telepac). We could access Videotex via a telephone line or a X.25 connection as long as we had the necessary NUA (Network User Address) credentials. The cool thing about our Videotex service was that it provided a bridge to other international services, like the Minitel.

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/ptvtx.jpg" text="A Portuguese bank announcing their Videotex service (video)" link="https://arquivos.rtp.pt/conteudos/sistema-de-videotexto-do-bnu/" >}}

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/loewe.jpg" text="The Loewe VTXTEL-CP terminal used in Portugal" >}}

I also remember using the university [X.25](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X.25) connection (before the Internet) to access Minitel, specifically to access [QSD](https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=24442211), a popular hacker chatroom service. Stories for another day.

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/qsd.jpg" text="QSD Chat" >}}

## What is the Telematico

The Telematico is a [videotex](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Videotex) terminal launched in 1988 specifically made for the Italian market to access their [Videotel](https://it.wikipedia.org/wiki/Videotel) service, which was similar to the French Minitel, and it allowed customers to access it through a terminal with a modem over the telephone line.

This terminal features a Z80 clocked at 3MHz, 32K ROM, 4K RAM, a 256 byte EEROM to save configurations, a CEPT Videotex Level 1 video decoder and a CCITT V.21 and V.23 (1200 baud) capable modem.

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/pcb.jpg" text="Telematico PCB" >}}

The Telematico is loosely based on the [MSX1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MSX#System_specifications) architecture, one that Philips knew very well because their also produced MSX computers, but not really. The ICs on the board are quite standard for this age of computers except the mysterious "Celint" Videotex decoder and video generator chip. More on this later.

Alright let's turn this thing on.

