## Bringing the Telematico online

The next step is connecting the terminal to another computer. This seems simple, but it obviously never is. There isn't a serial or parallel port, no expansion port, nothing, the only way out of this computer is its modem.

So my plan is connecting the Telematico modem to a cheap StartUSB USB modem hooked up to my Mac. Easy. Not.

You can't just connect an old modem to a another modem, they expect a real telephone line with certain electrical conditions between them. Specifically they require an active electrical current passing through the line to physically energize the loop so that they can detect that they are "off-hook," and activate their internal circuitry. Without voltage, the modem thinks the line is dead.

So we need to simulate that. This is how I tricked the Telematico modem into thinking it has a line it can dial in into, and a USB modem connected to my Mac into thinking it can answer (ATA) a call:

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/phoneline.png" text="Injecting 24V to simulate the off-hook voltage of a telephone line" >}}

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/loop.jpg" text="The circuit above in a small PCB" >}}

So now I created a phonebook entry on the Telematico that just dials "1" (the number doesn't matter, I just the modem to go off-hook and initiate a call) and is of type Videotel V23.

Time to get the Telematico online. I fire up minicom on the Mac, set the serial port to 115200 bps 8N1 and enable local echo, then I type the ATA modem command which instructs it to go "off-hook" and manually answer an incoming call, and at the same I initiate the call on the Telematico. Sure enough, I can hear the handshake negotiation and a few seconds later the two modems CONNECT.

{{< youtube RF16D74dgpI >}}

I can now type stuff in minicom and see it echoed in the Telematico, but something is wrong. If I type "abcdefgh0123456789" I get a garbled version on the other end.

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/garbled.jpg" text="Definetly not abcdefgh0123456789" >}}

This is surely a parity issue, I think. The norm back them, and I confirmed with the Minitel modem settings, was 7E1, not 8N1. I try 7E1 and nothing changes, same garbled result. Maybe two stop bits? Every data and parity setting I try changes nothing.

Maybe it's the USB modem settings? That wouldn't make any sense, it's different communication layers, I fiddle with every ATS register anyway, nothing.

Maybe it's minicom. I try old school tcl send/expect, fconfigure options, stty options, nothing words.

Maybe the communication settings are fine and it's something with the Telematico decoder or character set, I think, as I start probing stuff with the oscilloscope.

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/scope.jpg" text="Probing data lines inside the Telematico" >}}

This went on for weeks with any progress. I needed a lot more about the internal details of the Telematico if I was going to solve this, poking around the PCB without a schematics wasn't going to help me. But there is no schematics I can find online.

