## Data payload settings problem, solved

Now that I had the schematics I was able to track down character data coming from the Mac modem all the way to the I/O chip of the Telematico and I quickly realized that something was off.

Suppose that I'm sending the character "a" over the line using 7E1, I expect to see 10 bits on the other end, one 0 start bit, then the data 1000011 bits ("a" character LSB inverted), then a 1 even parity bit, and then a 1 stop bit. That is 0 1000011 1 1.

However what I was receiving was 0 1000011 0 1. The parity bit was wrong for the letter "a", it should be 1, but it's 0.

In fact, no matter what character I was sending, the parity bit was always 0.

It's almost as it's all being sent using 8N1 and not 7E1 which is what I have configured in the Mac terminal to use. How is this possible?

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/parity.png" text="This 8-line decoders tells us how the memory map is organized" >}}

It turns out that macOS's native AppleUSBACM USB serial driver defaults internally to CS8 (8 data bits) and completely ignores the POSIX command to alter data bit sizes or parity), it is strictly limited to raw binary no parity.

I couldn't believe it. Had I tried this on Linux or Windows and everything would have worked fine.

Anyway, the solution is simple, all we have to do is calculate the even parity bit in user land and send the data as raw binary.

```ts
const evenParity = (b) => {
  b &= 0x7f;
  b ^= b >> 4;
  b ^= b >> 2;
  b ^= b >> 1;
  return b & 1;
}

const to7E1 = (b) => {
  const data = b & 0x7f;
  const parity = evenParity(data);
  return data | (parity << 7);
}

const encoded = Buffer.from("abcdefgh0123456789").map(to7E1);

await writeSerial(port, encoded);
```

And now it works:

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/notgarbled.jpg" text="Yay" >}}

So now I have good communications with the Telematico. What's next?

## A Videotex server, powered by Cloudflare Workers

Next up, obviously, is I want to simulate a remote Videotex server and have the Telematico connect and interact with it.

I found the datasheet for the misterious Celint Videotex decoder in a dark corner of the Internet, it's actually a [GEC Plessey MR9735](https://github.com/celso/NMS3000/blob/main/datasheets/MR9735-video.pdf) Teletext/Viewdata 625-Line Video Generator, and it gives me enough clues to get me started:

- 24 row x 40 character display.
- Supports ASCII and oldest [CEPT Level 1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_System_Teletext#Level_1_(1976)) Videotex (002 character set).
- Supports [Viewdata](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viewdata) encoding.

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/charmap.jpg" text="002 character set" >}}

Alright, I think I can work with this.

What I plan to do is a Videotex server running on top Cloudflare Workers and Durable Objects that talks to clients over WebSocket connections. Then I run a WebSocket to RS232 proxy on my laptop that talks to my local USB StartTech modem which in turn is connected to the Telematico modem over a telephone line. Finally the cherry on top is that I also want a Web Videotex terminal so that I'm able to use a browser if I want to.

Here's a diagram that helps understand:

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/diagram.png" text="Diagram of my Cloudflare Workers powered Videotex server" >}}

So I half slop coded the Videotex Server to use [Cloudflare Workers](https://github.com/celso/NMS3000/blob/main/videotex-server/worker/index.ts). A Durable Object is used to handles the client sessions, their state, and their WebSocket connection. A WebSocket message can contain key strokes, videodata frames and other [control codes](https://github.com/celso/NMS3000/blob/main/videotex-server/worker/videotex.ts).

Then I have a Videotex Web Client that can be used with a browser. I coded it with [Vite+React](https://github.com/celso/NMS3000/blob/main/videotex-server/src/main.tsx) and used the fantastic [@techandsoftware/teletext](https://www.npmjs.com/package/@techandsoftware/teletext) package that can render teletext pages to SVG.

{{< caption image="/assets/telematico/webvideotex.png" text="Diagram of my Cloudflare Workers powered Videotex server" >}}

You can actually git it a try at https://videotex.arkanoid.workers.dev/


